\begin_layout Title
Status consumption under wealth inequalities 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

- a case study in Tanzania
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract

\shape italic
Status consumption is known to be ubiquitous but the role played by wealth
 inequalities in the varied contexts of developing economies has been explored
 less often.
 We use a model for status consumption that view the expenditure in excess
 of needs relative the permanent ownership as non-durable status consumption
 and comment on the opposing effects of peer influences and extreme wealth
 differences in the developing countries.
 Using the consumption data from the Tanzanian LSMS survey we discuss how
 a segregation of status competition based on extreme wealth differences
 and price heterogeneity could characterise status consumption in a developing
 economy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
