LatexCommand cite
key "ChaiKaus2019,KausSA,ZahraIndia,JaikumarConspConIneq,FrieheGermany,heffetz_visibility"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 While such disparities are often explained with social-reference groups,
 the ways in which status consumption differ under the environment of extreme
 poverty in developing countries has been explored less often.
 Noting prevalent wealth inequalities in the developing economies, we reexamine
 the notion of status with a particular focus on the opposing direction
 of peer effects and the effects of wealth differences on status consumption.
 Status consumption - which is undoubtedly enhanced with peer effects -
 should be discouraged under extreme wealth differences when the latter
 cannot be overcome by the consumer.
 Contrary to the idea of pecuniary emulation
