 of socio-economic differences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Status competition among the consumers that are strictly segregated across
 spatial or socio-economic boundaries (e.g.
 class, region, race etc.) are evidently segmented across the groups.
 But while the poor may not emulate the rich separated by huge wealth difference
s, the status competitions are not limited to one's own reference group
 either.
 The consumers infer the status of other reference groups which they don't
 belong to just as well as they compare themselves with the participants
 in their own reference groups.
 The extent to which status consumption is driven by the level of segregation
 in an economy is the quantitative concern our model for status is concerned
 with.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Building upon the social-deference view of status that has been embraced
 in many economic studies 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KoutsobinasStatusPoliticalEconomy,corneo_snobbism,ColemanSocialTheory1990"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, we use a model where status consumption is used to offset the effect of
 existing wealth hierarchies towards status.
 Any two consumers in the model thus compete with each other for status
 using both the permanent ownership of items and the excess non-durable
 consumption (i.e.
 consumption above the cost of needs) .
 For the empirical measurement of the permanent ownership of items we rely
 on the long term durable goods data available for every household in the
 survey.
 The excess non-durable consumption is measured using the cost of needs
 - which in comprises of the cost of basic needs varying across regions
 and the cost of owning long-term goods (also available in the survey).
 After adjusting for her needs, a consumer optimises the utility she obtains
 from both excess and long-term possessions.
 Social or spatial characteristics matter to the consumer in the model through
 both the durable goods cluster which the consumer belongs to and the price
 of needs that the consumer is exposed to.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In popular culture, status consumption often evokes images of wasteful expenditu
re and exclusive possessions that provide no economic value other than an
 attraction to people of equal affluence.
 This rather inadequate view of status consumption is source of an incessant
 debate on whether a consumer's newly acquired wealth - whether it be jewelry
 of acquisition of undervalued land or property - should be considered part
 of her necessities for higher status or wasteful conspicuous consumption.
 Since we have no way of knowing the intentions of consumers by evaluating
 her consumption diaries, we focus only on the measurements of existing
  wealth and an incontrovertible notion of basic necessities instead of
 drawing normative judgments on the appropriate level of needs for the consumer.
 We rely on a notion of basic needs in an economy to infer a notion of excess
 – so that the rich in an economy do not inherently have needs different
 from the poor - instead only different levels of excess over basic needs
 and the disparate long-term possessions.
 The notion of excess also excludes any maintenance costs for the long-term
 possession the role of which towards status is considered explicitly.
 For example, if one has a car, the petrol used up for driving is not an
 excess and contributes only to the cost of bearing assets.
 As consumer are meant to use to both excess and long-term ownership for
 status competitions excess and since excess vary according to a particular
 asset-cluster / band
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}$
\end_inset

 one belongs, the idiosyncratic habits are expected to average out for the
 notion of excess relative to durable goods ownership.
 This is admissible since the empirical claim that we wish to test is whether
 non-durable status consumption - viewed as excess over needs - is dominated
 by status competition in the local wealth hierarchy or those among the
 consumers of similar wealth in a spatial proximity.
 The significance of the metrics related to wealth at local and national
 levels help us comment if local peer effects are more important for the
 consumer than the differences in wealth at observed the higher level in
 the wider economy.
 We believe that this detail of non-durable status consumption is more relevant
 to how status motivations influence urban migration or demand for industrial
 items than the analysis of visible items in the economy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The key appeal of the above approach is that unlike with the studies in
 visible consumption, one needs not rely on the assumption that status goods
 are futile.
 While the futility assumption implicitly ensures the separability of demand
