\begin_layout Standard
The notion of status most commonly used in literature is one where it is
 seen as a long-term characteristics of the consumer.
 The view of status as a static characteristic in fact poses an obvious
 paradox with respect to consumption - since there cannot be any utility
 from status-consumption if status were only accumulated over a long-term.
 The paradox is trivially resolved if one considers that status is subject
 to change with consumption - just the way it is shaped by income or education
 (see Michelson et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MichelsonMunizDeRose2013"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and Psake et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PsakiSeidman2013"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 where status - like in many studies in sociology and health sciences -
 is used as a vector education or income ).
 The dynamic view of status - provided by Coleman
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ColemanSocialTheory1990"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and Corneo et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "corneo_snobbism"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and having been widely embraced in the economic studies - presents status
 as an wealth-based ranking order that can be altered by the consumer with
 consumption.
 A consumer thus achieves status utility through status consumption by moving
 herself up in a ranking order that is otherwise determined by wealth.
 A model that that views consumption in the context of status as a ranking
 order based on income or wealth could be used to endogenise the role of
 social identity in conspicuous consumption as well.
 This is the view used in our intertemporal formulation of status consumption.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even though the role which social identities play in status consumption
 has been explored in much of the literature (see Chao et al.
 [#Chao1998], Charles et al.
 [#CharlesHurstRace], Omori et al.
 [#OmoriSmithVisRace], Kaus[#KausSA] and Khamis et al.[#ZahraIndia] - also
 see the marketing literature on identity formation and acquired goods [#gierl_s
carcity, #Eastman1999]), the relevance of wealth differences in status consumpti
on has not been discussed in much detail in the literature on conspicuous
 consumption we have surveyed (except for some studies directly exploring
 the effect income inequality on conspicuous consumption with exogenously
 observed poverty/income levels or GINI indices - see Jaikumar 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "JaikumarConspConIneq"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Wisman 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "WismanSavingClassIdentity2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Chai et al
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
