 If basic needs of the two consumers being compared are the same and their
 difference in needs arise only out of their long-term possessions, then
 the addressing of needs alone does not provide any status utility than
 what is provided by the long-term possessions or characteristics.
 It follows that if there is any status related utility to be derived from
 non-durable consumption, it would be constituted in the felicity from excess
 (which is defined as distance from all needs tied to a particular reference
 group).
 It also follows that any status in a particular reference group that is
 not signaled with excess must come out of the possession of (and thus utility
 from) the long-term durable goods (or the proxy of wealth).
\end_layout

